SIMPLE: patronymic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patronymic
<hw>Pa`tro*nym"ic</hw> <pr>(-n⟦icr⟧m"⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>patronymicus</ets>, Gr. <grk>patrwnymiko`s</grk>;
<grk>path`r</grk> father + <grk>'o`noma</grk> name: cf. F.
<ets>patronymique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Derived from ancestors; <as>as, a
<ex>patronymic</ex> denomination</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patronymic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Patronymic
<hw>Pa`tro*nym"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>patrwnymiko`n</grk>.]</ety> <def>A modification of the father's
name borne by the son; a name derived from that of a parent or ancestor;
<as>as, <examp>Pelides</examp>, the son of Peleus;
<examp>Johnson</examp>, the son of John; <examp>Macdonald</examp>, the
son of Donald; <examp>Paulowitz</examp>, the son of Paul</as>; also, the
surname of a family; the family name.</def> <rj><au>M. A.
Lower.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In <country>Russia</country>, the <ex>patronymic</ex> is
taken routinely as a middle name, and is commonly used together with the
given name in addressing people with whom one is familiar, thus
<examp>Ivan Ivanovich</examp> would be commonly used to address Ivan,
whose father was Ivan; likewise <examp>Boris Michaelovich</examp> would
address Boris the son of Michael, and <examp>Lena Ivanova</examp> would
address Lena, the daughter of Ivan.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patronymical</ent>⟦br⟧
